The Legend of Robin Hood
By Craig Dutton (c) 2013

Loxley, South Yorkshire, 1182.

The sun rode high over the dark forest as a man dressed in Lincoln green ran for his life through the gnarled trees. Dogs barked their bloodthirsty menace with soldiers close behind them. They had chased their quarry for miles and were getting closer. Over ditch and under bough the hunted relented little until his exhaustion paid a heavy toll and he collapsed on the ground landing on some sharp brambles. As the hounds closed in a dark-haired man in black stood over the poor wretch and smiled a sickly grin.

'So, Loxley, how the mighty have fallen. Give me the arrow and I will let you die quickly!' he demanded.

'Only the worthy may possess it and you have never possessed such qualities. Your dogs have better breeding than you.' he gasped.

His smile faltered slightly as he ordered the soldiers to release the hounds. As the screams faded throughout the forest he picked up the solid silver arrow from the mutilated corpse. It glistened from the filtered sunlight above him and he bore that sickly grin again.

'So this is Herne's arrow! A treasure worthy of a Sheriff, I dare say.' he laughed and blended into the trees leaving his murderous deed behind him.

Sherwood Forest, Nottinghamshire, 1192.

You step out of the darkness of the huge oaks to emerge on to a forest road. You start recalling the mysterious death of your Father ten years ago to this very day. Unanswered questions lay heavy on your heart when a deer distracts your melancholy. The deer looks at you with its curious dark eyes. A sudden noise emanating from the depths of the forest alarms the creature and it bounds eastwards through the trees.

It looks like your next meal warrants a chase. You laugh and wonder if the Sheriff's men are going to be uninviting themselves again upon your land and claim that shooting a King's deer is an executable offence? Only if the deer itself takes offence to being shot. You laugh again. It was a shame they didn't think it funny.

'Now where did that deer go?' you cry.

