> up

> up
You all escape the castle by a lapse in the guards security -  they left the front gate open - and head for Sherwood Forest. The Sheriff proclaims you all as outlaws and you make camp in the deepest part of the forest. You call it Greenwood and moreover - home. Here you will stay and wonder how you can survive.

'We could always rob the rich.' suggests Will.

'An give it to the poor.' adds Much.

You look at Much and think he has a point. The Sheriff is always taking from the poor even when they have nothing at all. The look on his face would be priceless if we gave back to the needy that was forcibly taken by the 'Sheriff of Rottingham' as Much nicknamed him.

The Great Hall, Nottingham Castle

The Sheriff and Gisbourne are discussing ways to recapture Loxley.

'No one has even escaped my dungeon before. He must be taken alive so I can execute him before the peasants and make an example of him. I need to show an iron glove of power. He has humiliated me, Gisbourne.' shouts the Sheriff.

'I will personally see to it myself to recapture him for you, my Lord.' whimpers Guy.

'No, wait!' muses the Sheriff, 'I have a better plan. He needs to come to us willingly. I hear Loxley is a keen archer. I will hold an archery contest at the upcoming fair. But we need bait... I have it. Fetch me that silver arrow from my repository. I believed it belonged to his wretched father. A symbol of hope for the downtrodden but a hope of capturing an outlaw, Gisbourne,' he laughs, 'He won't be able to resist.'

A few weeks later deep in Sherwood Forest

You were wandering the forest when you hear rushing water up ahead. You come to a shallow river with a narrow bridge spanning across it. However, as you try to cross the bridge a large giant of a man stands in your way and refuses to step aside.

'I say, stranger. Make way - this is a public bridge!' you demand.

'Stranger or not I will not let you pass without a challenge. After all, a little bird like yourself could just fly across this little stream.' he laughs.

'What is your name, giant? I feel it is impolite to defeat a man of such stature without proper introduction.'

'John Little and what pray is your name?' he frowns.

'Robin of Loxley. Although locals have recently renamed me 'Robin of the Hood' because of my attire. I am an outlaw, John Little, pay heed or receive a soaking.'

'Robin! You are a little bird, indeed. Fly away or prepare for battle. Find yourself a quarterstaff as only pride rather than blood should fall this day.'

