You can go southeast.
You can see an Archery Official.
> give two silver coins to archery official

> give two silver coins to archery official
'Let the contest begin!' he shouts as two more competitors join you.

The rules are simple. There are two rounds. You get to fire an arrow at the target first and the other competitors follow you. The two closest to get an arrow in the centre of the target moves on to the final round. Whoever gets closest to the centre of the target in the final round wins the silver arrow.
> use bow on target

> use bow on target
You fire your arrow into the target and you hit the centre of the bullseye. Adam the Butcher goes next and hits the outer circle. Barnabus the Tailor goes last and hits the bullseye like yourself. You and Barnabus are through to the final round.

Barnabus goes first and hits the centre of the bullseye perfectly. The only chance of winning is by some miracle. It's your turn now.
> use bow on target

> use bow on target
As if your prayers were answered, you fire your arrow and it whistles into the target and actually splits Barnabus' arrow right down the middle. You have won! Time to receive your prize from the Sheriff who enters the field with Gisbourne.
> speak to sheriff

> speak to sheriff
'Congratulations, young man. Here is your prize.' he scowls as he reluctantly hands you the silver arrow.

'Tell me, stranger,' interrupts Gisbourne, 'Who are you that showed fine archery skills this very day? Come on, don't be shy.'

Gisbourne pulls off your hood and laughs. 'I knew it! It's Robin Hood! Guards, arrest this criminal!' he screams.

You push Gisbourne into the path of the Sheriff and they both fall over. You make your escape. However, one of the guards cuts you with his sword and you cry in pain dripping blood down your arm. An hour later you and your men are safely at Greenwood.

'That was too close, Robin.' puffs Little John catching his breath.

'Next time, Robin, you should make it much harder for us all.' laughs Will.

You look at the silver arrow and smile. 'That was for you, Father' you whisper as you find a safe place to store it.

King Richard's Kidnapping, December, 1192.

News reaches Greenwood telling you that King Richard the Lionheart, on returning from the Crusades, was kidnapped by Duke Leopold of Austria. He was, in turn, given to Henry VI, Holy Roman Emperor who is demanding 150,000 marks for his safe return to England.

You vow to raise this ransom and start with the silver arrow. However, it won't be enough and you need to think on how to raise more funds.

A week later.

You haven't been to church for ages since you became an outlaw and risk visiting Saint Mary's chapel at the Abbey. You will make a prayer for King Richard and your Father. You will also meet up with your old friend Brother Tuck who you haven't seen for a while and ask his advice on how to raise Richard's ransom.

You are in the abbey cloisters.  A rectangular open space surrounded by covered walks, with open arcades on the inner side running along the walls of the abbey and forming a quadrangle.
You can go in.
> in

> in

You are in the nave.  This is the main body of the church from entrance to the chancel.  Aisles run east and west by the seats on the north and south sides of the church walls.
You can go out or east.
You can see Brother Tuck.
> speak to brother tuck

> speak to brother tuck
'Robin, how is the life of an outlaw? The fresh air has certainly ruddied your cheeks,' Tuck laughs, 'What brings you to Saint Mary's?'

'Did you hear about the King's kidnapping?' you ask.

'Indeed I did. A travesty to all of England. I presume you have taken it upon yourself to raise his ransom?'

'You know me so well, Tuck, I have already regained Herne's Arrow and wonder if you know of any treasure to increase the coffers?'

'I had heard the Bishop of Hereford donated a considerable sum to the Sheriff quite recently in return for not disclosing his carnal activities to the Archbishop. A considerable sum that would no doubt release King Richard from his bondage. The Sheriff keeps it in his repository in his castle. Now are you here to repent your sins or has the Devil acquired a new disciple?' mocks Tuck.

'I'm here to say a prayer to the King and my Father.'

'Then, God be with you, my son.' nods Tuck and leave you to your thoughts.
> east

> east
Brother Tuck waves goodbye as you leave and disappears himself.

You are in the chancel.  This is the east part of the church where a stone altar rests upon a raised dais. Stone spiral steps lead up to the belfry.
You can go west or up.
> kneel

> kneel
You kneel before the altar.
> pray

> pray
You pray to the King and your Father. As you kneel in silence, eyes closed, a noise makes you look up and are shocked to see a figure head to toe in black stealing the silver chalice off the altar. You both stare at each other for a second before he runs upstairs to the belfry.
> up

> up
You stand up first to leave.

You are in the belfry.  In front of you is a large iron bell. Steps lead down to the chancel.
You can go down.
You can see a masked stranger.
> push bell

> push bell
You push the bell into the stranger with a loud CLANG and you knock him out.
> remove mask

> remove mask
You take off the mask and are shocked to see your childhood sweetheart Marian looking back at you! You revive Marian and she gives you a stern look.

'That hurt, Robin. Never study campanology.' she scolds.

'Sorry, Marian, but dressed like that I didn't know who you were. And by the way, why were you stealing the chalice?'

'I know you to well. You would find any way to raise King Richard's ransom and so I thought this might help.' says Marian sheepishly.

'There is no need, Marian, Brother Tuck has told me about the Sheriff's treasure at the castle.'

'I thought it would be too risky. I'm currently staying with the Sheriff at the moment. I was on my way home from Salisbury and stayed the night - much to the Sheriff's and Guy's delight, no doubt. I could stay a bit longer and spy on them if you would like.'

'I couldn't ask that of you, Marian.'

'It would be my pleasure, Robin.'

You and Marian suddenly catch a moment together but you both quickly snap out of it.

'Eh... be careful, Marian. I'll send word if I need your help.'

You leave your own separate ways and you head back to Greenwood.

The Raid on Nottingham Castle

A few days later Brother Tuck arrives with a message from Marian. She tells you, in her note, that most of the Sheriff's men have left Nottingham Castle on an important errand and tonight would be a good time to steal the treasure. You send Tuck back with a message to Marian, informing her that you agree and can she open the castle gate somehow at around midnight.

With the plan set in place you and your men enter Nottingham Castle and deal with any remaining guards scattered around the castle.

