Epilogue

After returning to camp, Robin tried to persuade Marian to return home but she refused. They both fell in love and Marian was declared an outlaw by the Sheriff. The treasure and the silver arrow paid for King Richard's ransom and what remained was given to the poor. This, in turn, became the main reason why Robin, Marian and the Merry Men continued as outlaws.

King Richard eventually returned to England in March, 1194.

Robin and Marian got married at Saint Mary's Church in Edwinstowe. She fought for many years by Robin's side.

After years of loyal service to Robin, Tuck retired with his dogs as Clerk of Companhurst.

Will Scarlet's life was a troubled one. After questioning Robin's decisions for many years he left to get married and never returned to Greenwood. However, his wife was murdered shortly afterwards, and he avenged her death by killing her murderers. Will joined another band of outlaws but was killed during a failed robbery.

Allen a Dale rescued his true love, Ellen, from marrying a rich, cruel knight. With the help of Robin and the Merry Men, they stopped the wedding, fought the knight and rescued Ellen.

Much grew up fast and was even as tall as Little John. Over twenty years later, Robin decided to retire and Much became leader. He adopted Robin's appellation to keep the hope and symbol of Robin Hood alive.

When Little John died he was buried at Hathersage, Yorkshire where he originally came from and his grave can be seen at Saint Michael's church to this day. The inscription reads on his grave:

Here Lies Buried Little John The Friend & Lieutenant of Robin Hood He Died In A Cottage (Now Destroyed) To The East of The Churchyard The Grave Is Marked By This Old Headstone & Footstone And Is Underneath The Old Yew.

In 1784 Captain James Shuttleworth exhumed the grave to find the bones of a man over seven feet tall.

During his dying days, Robin shot an arrow in the air and where it landed was where Little John buried him. His grave is believed to be located at Kirklees, Yorkshire. His epitaph reads (in a non-classified Middle English):

Hear underneath dis laitl stean
Laz robert earl of Huntingtun
Ne’er arcir ver as hie sa geud
An pipl kauld im robin heud
Sick [such] utlawz as he an iz men
Vil england nivr si agen
Obiit 24 kal: Dekembris, 1247.

In the 18th century, Thomas Gale, Dean of York, claimed to have found a poetic epitaph with the date of death given as 8 November 1247, which is the date in the modern calendar that corresponds to 24 Dekembris in the calendar in use in 1247. Two Elizabethan-era stage plays on the Robin Hood legend, that were written by Anthony Munday (possibly with help from Henry Chettle) in 1598 and published in 1601 name him as Robert, Earl of Huntington.

Whenever he died the Legend of Robin Hood will live on for a long time to come...

The End
